Bring your picnic dinner and join this fall tradition with music by Reed, Jager, and Sousa at the Gazebo with the Symphonic Wind Band. In the case of inclement weather, we’ll move inside to Stratton Hall.

A special encore performance to highlight and support the work at Piedmont Women's Center.
 
Piedmont Women's Center is a pro-life pregnancy medical clinic that provides free gospel-centered medical and support services for women facing an unplanned pregnancy.

Proceeds from this performance will support the mission and work of Piedmont Women's Center.

A Medieval comedy, Argus and the Maze of Myth follows young Argus, a cowardly squire who dreams of becoming a knight. He serves under the proud yet clumsy knight, Sir William. Their mission: to save the Fair Maiden trapped within the labyrinth. This journey is anything but a brisk walk in the meadows. They will encounter mythical creatures, secrets, and even a little goat. Join in the adventure as they brave the Maze of Myth!

items.summary: Faculty Recital: Isaac Greene & Nathan MacAvoy
items.description: Join Drs. Nathan MacAvoy and Isaac Greene of the Division of Music for a dynamic program of chamber music for the unusual combination of guitar and piano or guitar and harpsichord. Featuring four works of the 20th century, this program is sure to introduce you to something new and exciting.

items.summary: Play: Sorry, Wrong Number & Blind Date
items.description: Two one-act plays presented by the Theatre department. Sorry, Wrong Number follows the tale of a fearful invalid, whose only contact with the outside world is her phone. One night, because of a crossed wire, she hears plans for a murder which turns out to be her own. Blind Date is touching and very funny study of what befalls a fluttery, well-meaning aunt when she tries to arrange a date for her visiting (and uncooperative) niece. Both productions are produced by special arrangement with Dramatists Play Service www.dramatists.com.

An exciting, fast-moving concert featuring student soloists and ensembles from the Division of Music at BJU.

Join the University Singers, Bob Jones University’s dynamic freshman choir, for an inspiring evening of choral music. Composed of first-year students from a variety of majors, these musicians offer a heartfelt performance that reflects their developing artistry and shared love of choral singing.

BJU’s 96-year-old Classical Theatre Troupe, Classic Players, presents Shakespeare’s King Lear. Family, politics and lies collide in one of Shakespeare’s greatest tragedies. King Lear chronicles King Lear’s decision to divide his kingdom among his three daughters and the disaster that follows.

Intended for students age 12+ and their primary educators. Contact Programs & Productions to secure tickets, (864) 770-1372 or in person.  

Online ticketing is not available.

Join the BJU Concert Choir under the direction of Laura Brundage for “Simple Gifts.” From the rolling hills of Appalachia to the Windswept Highlands of Scotland, this program weaves together folk tunes, spirituals, and lyrical settings that speak to love, longing, and joy. Featuring works by John Rutter, Bob Chilcott, Stephen Paulus, Rene´ Clausen, and others, Simple Gifts invites you into a world where music honors tradition, stirs the soul, and uplifts the heart.
